- tCHAPTER 18. Classical Theory and the Labor Cartel -- tCHAPTER 19. Coercion and Its Meaning: Antitrust and the Labor Injunction -- tPART VI. THE ANTITRUST MOVEMENT AND THE THEORY OF THE FIRM -- tCHAPTER 20. American Merger Policy and the Failure of Corporate Law -- tCHAPTER 21. The Classical Theory of Competition -- tCHAPTER 22. The Rise of Industrial Organization -- tCHAPTER 23. The Fixed-Cost Controversy -- tCHAPTER 24. Potential Competition -- tCHAPTER 25. Vertical Integration and Resale Price Maintenance -- tEpilogue: Classical Enterprise in Decline -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this integration of law and economic ideas, Herbert Hovenkamp charts the evolution of the legal framework that regulated American business enterprise from the time of Andrew Jackson through the first New Deal. He reveals the interdependent relationship between economic theory and law that existed in these decades of headlong growth and examines how this relationship shaped both the modern business corporation and substantive due process. Classical economic theory--the cluster of ideas about free markets--became the guiding model for the structure and function of both private and public law. Hovenkamp explores the relationship of classical economic ideas to law in six broad areas related to enterprise in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. He traces the development of the early business corporation and maps the rise of regulated industry from the first charterbased utilities to the railroads. He argues that free market political economy provided the intellectual background for constitutional theory and helped define the limits of state and federal regulation of business behavior. The book also illustrates the unique American perspective on political economy reflected in the famous doctrine of substantive due process. Finally, Hovenkamp demonstrates the influence of economic theory on labor law and gives us a reexamination of the antitrust movement, the most explicit intersection of law and economics before the New Deal. Legal, economic, and intellectual historians and political scientists will welcome these trenchant insights on an influential period in American constitutional and corporate history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAntitrust law. 0aAntitrustrecht. 0aBedrijfsleven. 0aCorporation law. 0aGesellschaftsrecht. 0aIndustrial policy. 0aRecht. 0aTrade regulation. 0aWetgeving. 0aWirtschaftsrecht. 4aAntitrust law -- United States -- History. 4aCorporation law -- United States -- History. 4aIndustrial policy -- United States -- History. 4aTrade regulation -- United States -- History. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Law & Political Science eBook Packagez9783110353495oZDB-23-HLP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067433556140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067433558540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674335585423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674335585/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-HCO  aZDB-23-HLP